1. Definition
The Hamming distance between two equal-length sequences is the count of positions at which the corresponding elements differ. Applicable to binary vectors, characters in strings (when compared as code points), and fixed-length tokens.

2. Mathematical formula
For sequences x and y of length n:
  d(x,y) = sum_{i=0..n-1} (x_i != y_i ? 1 : 0)
For binary integer values interpreted as bit-vectors of width W:
  d(a,b) = popcount(a XOR b)

3. Efficient implementations
- Bitwise (integers): compute XOR, then compute population count (popcount) of the XOR result. Use hardware popcount when available (e.g., GCC __builtin_popcount, CPU POPCNT instruction).
- Software popcount: Kernighan's method: repeatedly clear lowest set bit: count = 0; while (v) { v &= v - 1; count++; }
- Table lookup: split word into bytes/nibbles, use precomputed table to sum set bits.
- Strings: normalize comparison unit to code points (not UTF-16 code units) when comparing textual characters across languages or surrogate pairs. Use an iterator that yields full Unicode code points and compare code points one-by-one.

4. JavaScript string considerations
- JS String length is in UTF-16 code units; surrogate pairs occupy two code units. Comparing by code unit will miscount differences for characters outside BMP.
- Use for...of or String.prototype.codePointAt to iterate/inspect by code point. When comparing two strings for Hamming distance as sequences of characters, first ensure they have the same number of code points; if not, define desired behavior (error, pad, or normalize) before computing.
- For binary data use Node.js Buffer objects (byte arrays) and compute XOR per byte then sum set bits per byte.

5. Complexity and edge cases
- Time complexity: O(n) where n is number of elements compared (bits, bytes, or code points).
- Space: O(1) extra beyond inputs for streaming comparisons.
- Edge cases: differing lengths, normalization (NFC/NFD) of Unicode, combining marks, grapheme clusters vs code points (graphemes require more advanced segmentation if intended semantics are 'characters' as visible glyphs).

